<b>New Rules for XP with Pets! - </b>7/2/02 1:29:02 PM<br>~ <b>Klapton Groovemaster</b><blockquote>To get the proper XP when charm soloing, you MUST inflict some damage yourself on the mob.  Charm, /pet attack, F1 twice to ensure your pet is targeted for recharm, then Chords, DDD.  Back off then as far as you can within sight with charm song on.  Space permitting, your pet will recharm before he gets to you.  Also, once he is on the mob, back off just enough to be out of the target mobs range, but still close enough to AE zap em.<br><br>It takes practice, and you must be able to switch instruments as you twist.  See some of the quality twisting guides available online.<br><br>Klapton Groovemaster<br>37 Rock Legend<br>Vazaelle Server</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Other strategies - </b>2/2/02 12:25:03 AM<br>~ <b>Aeronica Songweaver</b><blockquote>When charming kiting, apply songs like Largo's Melodic Binding or Brusco's Boastful Bellow to the mob your pet is attacking.  Be sure to keep your distance.  The reason why I have done this instead of charming the winning mob is because I have found that if I switch a charm target, the mob that was charmed will attack me and it becomes difficult to get mob off.<br>If I apply largo's to one mob and the charm breaks on my pet, I only have one mob to worry about.  Just re-charm pet, order it to attack other mob, and re-apply Largo's.  I find this strategy most useful against even con'd mobs because I know they are same level.  You can't be 100% sure of level if mob is con'd blue.  My charisma is 121 and wind skill is maxxed.</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Great for many occasions... - </b>1/26/02 6:20:09 PM<br>~ <b>Fluellen Cadwaladr</b><blockquote>For some time, since I simply couldn't get the hang of charm-kiting, I used this to charm adds in battle, which was an adequate use.<br><br>After that, I began mixing it in with my all-instruments aoe attack--CoD, DDD, heal, charm whatever's attacking me, press ESC (new mob will be my target), CoD, DDD, heal... this was actually fairly effective in groups of high greens, but not really all that great.<br><br>Finally got the hang of charm kiting from 38 to 39 in Great Divide, against Drakkel Dire Wolves, and I must say it worked well.  I had best luck with the &quot;charm, run past uncharmed and take a hit, heal with lute, heal with lute, recharm, repeat&quot; technique, then polished off the remaining critter with FCC/CoF.<br><br>But the &quot;ding&quot; that got my 39 was my first real experience with swarm-kiting--better late than never!  Target pet, charm, be whomped by many wolves; by the time charm breaks pet has taken significant damage--either charm for another round or switch to drum, FCC/CoF/selo's to kill the ex-pet, then start again.  I was able to solo six drakkel dire wolves at once in this fashion, and while I did finish the experiment with only 1.5 bubbles of health, the XP and faction was fantastic.<br><br>Just got the charm &quot;upgrade&quot; at 39 and it does seem to burn mana pretty quickly--no matter, but it's a concern and something to watch for.<br><br>Still, the charm series can be fantastic both in and out of groups.  In groups, I STRONGLY encourage you to use a &quot;charming&quot; macro which lets your group know what mob you're charming; your melee types will thank you for not confusing them, and the casters will love you for not burning their mana.<br><br>:Fluellen Cadwaladr:<br></blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
